# Pre-commit review checklist (ResearchOne)

This list exists because the agent shipped 22 reviewer-caught bugs across
PRs #36–#40, and every single one was in a recurring class. Reading and
walking through this list takes ~60 seconds per commit. The retrospective
that drove this list is at `docs/retrospectives/2026-04-28-pr36-40-review-findings.md`.

## A. Before staging

1. **Read the full file**, not just the diff, around every edit. About a
   third of the bugs were visible only when the surrounding function or
   call site was read end-to-end.
2. **Grep for every remaining caller** of any primitive you changed. If
   you renamed/retyped/restricted/loosened a function or constant,
   search the repo (`Grep`) for its name and confirm each caller is
   either updated or still correct. (See
   `.cursor/rules/17-ripple-and-grep-callers.mdc`.)
3. **Grep for every other writer** of any data field you changed. If
   you wrote `failure_meta.terminal=true` in one place, find every
   other writer of `failure_meta` and confirm none can produce a
   contradictory value. (See
   `.cursor/rules/10-state-machine-and-multi-writer.mdc`.)

## B. Tests

4. **Tests must fail in the absence of the fix.** Mentally revert the
   fix and confirm the new test fails. If it would still pass, the
   test is asserting too little. (See
   `.cursor/rules/16-tests-must-fail-without-the-fix.mdc`.)
5. **Order-sensitive tests must assert order**, not just call counts.
6. Run `npx tsc --noEmit` and `npx vitest run` locally **after** each
   meaningful edit, not just at the end.

## C. Async / state correctness

7. **Two async sources updating the same fact** → there is a window where
   they disagree. Decide which one wins and document it. (See
   `.cursor/rules/10-state-machine-and-multi-writer.mdc`.)
8. **Side effect first, DB row second.** If a row "promises" a downstream
   side effect (a queued job, a sent email), do the side effect before
   writing the row that promises it. (See
   `.cursor/rules/13-deploy-skew-and-schema.mdc`.)

## D. Error paths and logs

9. **Don't lose diagnostic logging when narrowing an error path.** If
   you `throw` early in a `catch` block, copy the same `logger.warn` /
   `logger.error` calls the rest of the codebase relies on. (See
   `.cursor/rules/11-error-paths-and-logging.mdc`.)
10. **Don't reuse a callback for a new severity level.** If `onError` is
    wired to `notify('error', …)`, do not pass success-path strings
    through it; add `onInfo` / `onSuccess`. (See same rule.)

## E. Schema / deploy / migrations

11. **Code that depends on a migration must tolerate the migration not
    having applied yet.** Wrap the SELECT/UPDATE in try/catch on
    Postgres `42703` (column does not exist) or `22P02` (invalid enum
    value) and degrade to safe defaults. (See
    `.cursor/rules/13-deploy-skew-and-schema.mdc`.)
12. **Fallback UPDATEs must mirror the primary UPDATE's writes**, not
    be a stripped-down subset. (See same rule.)
13. **`ALTER TYPE … ADD VALUE` cannot run inside a transaction**. The
    migrate runner honors `-- @migrate:no-transaction`; use it.

## F. Event windowing

14. **`[new, ...prev].slice(-150)` drops the new event** when prev is
    already at the limit. Use `[...prev, new].slice(-150)` for
    "newest-at-bottom, drop oldest." (See
    `.cursor/rules/12-event-window-math.mdc`.)

## G. Third-party APIs

15. **Read the contract of any third-party API you call**. BullMQ
    `Job.remove()` throws on locked jobs. OpenRouter slugs use `:` for
    variants; HF repo ids never do. Postgres `ALTER TYPE ADD VALUE`
    can't be in a tx. (See
    `.cursor/rules/14-third-party-api-contracts.mdc`.)

## H. Doc / PR body parity

16. **PR body and header docs must reference symbols that actually
    exist in the patch.** Re-read the body against the final commit
    diff before pushing. (See
    `.cursor/rules/15-doc-pr-and-code-parity.mdc`.)
17. **Any external-system claim in a doc / PR body must be verified
    live.** "Multi-provider redundant on OpenRouter" requires
    actually hitting `/api/v1/models/<slug>/endpoints`. "Available on
    HF Inference" requires actually checking the model card. (See
    same rule.)

## I. Research policy guardrails (repo-specific)

18. **The binding V2 rule is inference-time behavior**, not training
    history. Read `docs/V2_MODEL_SELECTION_CRITERIA.md` and
    `ResearchOne PolicyOne` before changing any V2 default. RLHF /
    abliterated / uncensored are decision proxies, not the rule. See
    `.cursor/rules/20-research-policy-guardrails.mdc`.
19. **Critical-path V2 default primaries must have ≥ 2 live OpenRouter
    upstreams.** Verify per-slug live before claiming "multi-provider"
    in any doc / PR body. Single-upstream slugs are user-opt-in only.
    The `V2_FORBIDDEN_DEFAULT_MODELS` regression test and the startup
    pre-flight probe enforce this.
20. **`REASONING_FIRST_PREAMBLE` and `RED_TEAM_V2_SYSTEM_PREFIX` are
    immutable.** Do not edit their content; do not skip their
    application.

---

If a finding from a code review surprises the agent, add it to
`docs/retrospectives/` and (if it represents a class) extend the rule
that covers it. The rules are first-class artifacts of this repo.
